{{dictdef}} {{Emotion}} '''Outrage''' is a strong [[emotion]] characterized by a combination of [[surprise (emotion)|surprise]], [[disgust]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pss.sagepub.com/content/24/10/2069.abstract|title=The Interactive Effect of Anger and Disgust on Moral Outrage and Judgments|publisher=}}</ref> and [[anger]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adliterate.com/archives/Plutchik.emotion.theorie.POSTER.pdf |format=PDF |title=Robert POlutchik's Psychoevolutionary Theory of Basic Emotions |website=Adliterate.com |accessdate=2017-06-05}}</ref> usually in reaction to a grave personal offense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/outrage|title=Outrage – Definition of Outrage by Merriam-Webster|publisher=}}</ref> It comes from old French and meant "beyond [[rage (emotion)|rage]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/american_english/outrage|title=outrage: definition of outrage in Oxford dictionary (American English)|publisher=}}</ref>
'''Moral outrage''' is the emotion of outrage experienced in reaction to an [[injustice]], as such involving a [[moral judgement]].
